h authorization2star  aThis diverse collection explores the rhetoric of a wide range of public policies that propose "to put women and children first," including homeland security, school violence, gun control, medical intervention of intersex infants, and policies that aim to distinguish "good" from "bad" mothers. Using various feminist philosophical analyses, the contributors uncover a logic of paternalistic treatment of women and children that purports to protect them but almost always also disempowers them and sometimes harms them. This logic is widespread in contemporary popular policy discourse and affects the way that people understand and respond to social and political issues. Contributors rethink basic philosophical assumptions concerning subjectivity, difference, and dualistic logic in order to read the rhetoric of contemporary public policy discourse and develop new ways of talking and acting in the policy domain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aBuydens, Norma L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharles, Sonya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiQuinzio, Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiQuinzio, Patrice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeder, Ellen K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsgro, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManaghan, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela